[1] Thailand: suspected
Date: Sun 22 Jul 2012
Source: Bangkok Post [edited]
http://www.bangkokpost.com/news/local/303659/virus-which-closed-schools-suspected-in-infant-s-death


Virus which closed schools suspected in infant's death
------------------------------------------------------
Doctors suspect they have found the country's 1st fatality this year [2012] from enterovirus 71 (EV-71), which [among other enteroviruses] may cause hand, foot and mouth disease (HFMD), and will submit the case to a virologists' meeting on Tuesday [24 Jul 2012] for confirmation. Passakorn Chaivanichsiri, Director of Nopparat Rajathanee Hospital on Ram Intra Road [Bangkok], said EV-71 was thought to have been found in the body of a 2-and-a-half-year girl who died on 19 Jul 2012. He said the infant showed no related symptoms of the disease such as ulcers in the throat, mouth and tongue or any rash. She suffered damage to her heart, lungs and brain.

According to Dr Passakorn the hospital conducted a proper screening and diagnosis and the result came back negative for HFMD. However, "the results of a throat culture show [signs of] EV-71, a strain that can cause serious complications," he said.

A source close to the hospital said the infant was in critical condition when she was admitted to the hospital. The Disease Control Department earlier denied her death was caused by the HFMD virus after a lumbar puncture test and stool examination did not reveal the presence of the disease. The girl's father said his daughter had visited a school before she fell ill.

Pornthep Siriwanarangsan, director general of the Public Health Ministry's Disease Control department, urged parents not to be afraid of an outbreak of HFMD. He said the public health system's preventative measures are highly effective. A temporary shutdown of some schools is in place as a precaution to contain a likely outbreak.

According to Dr Pornthep, HFMD killed 6 people out of 18 196 patients last year [2011]. The mortality rate was 0.01 per 100 000 people. Dr Prasert Thongcharoen, an adviser to the Disease Control Department, said the laboratory tests on the girl will be submitted to virologists on Tuesday [24 Jul 2012] to confirm the cause of death. "Parents should not panic about this as the situation is not unusual. Over the past 5 years, Thailand has averaged 8000 - 18 000 HFMD patients a year with between 2 and 6 deaths," he said.

Public Health Minister Witthaya Buranasiri yesterday [21 Jul 2012] gave assurances that state and private hospitals are highly capable of handling HFMD. He said parents seem to be well informed about how to take action to stop the disease. He urged schools and child-care centres to maintain high hygiene standards even without any sign of an outbreak. "There is no need to wait for an outbreak to step up sanitation. Parents should wash their hands before holding their children. They must keep up their personal hygiene or they may pass on the disease to children," he said.

